        "summarize failed for https://maggieappleton.com/garden-history: {'ok': True, 'status': 200, 'elapsed_ms': 58458, 'body': {'title': 'Digital Gardening', 'summary': \"## Core Concept of Digital Gardening\\n- A departure from traditional blogs, emphasizing free-form, work-in-progress wikis.\\n- Ideas evolve and are linked by context, not reverse-chronological order.\\n- Characterized as less rigid, performative, and perfect, echoing the early web's ethos.\\n\\n## Evolution of the 'Digital Garden' Concept\\n- Mark Bernstein's 1998 essay 'Hypertext Gardens' first addressed user experience and content organization in the context of the '90s 'Navigation Problem'.\\n- A brief, unrelated usage appeared on Twitter in April 2007, where Rory Sutherland defined it as digital maintenance or 'faffing'.\\n- The modern concept is credited to Mike Caufield's 2015 keynote 'The Garden and the Stream', which positioned the garden as a long-term, explorable knowledge space in contrast to ephemeral social media 'streams'.\\n- Caufield's ideas gained traction in late 2018, amplified by Tom Critchlow's 'campfires' metaphor and Joel Hooks' 2019 writing on gardening as a process.\\n- Amy Hoy's argument that Moveable Type's 2001 launch standardized the reverse-chronological blog is cited as a contrast.\\n- By 2019-2020, the concept was expanded by Shaun Wang and Anne-Laure Le Cunff, discussed by the IndieWeb community, and covered by MIT Tech Review.\\n\\n## Community and Technological Support\\n- The trend's growth was supported by communities such as IndieWeb, Roam Research users, and followers of 'Building a Second Brain' and 'Learn in Public' philosophies.\\n- Early adopters were often developers utilizing tools like Netlify, Vercel, and static site generators (Jekyll, Gatsby).\\n- No-code tools like Obsidian, TiddlyWiki, and Notion now offer less customizable options for non-technical users.\\n\\n## Key Characteristics and Patterns\\n\\n### Topography over Timelines\\n- Prioritizes contextual, bi-directional links over chronological dates.\\n\\n### Continuous Growth\\n- Notes are never considered finished and are expected to evolve publicly.\\n\\n### Imperfection & Learning in Public\\n- Embraces a 'Domestic Cozy' approach, requiring transparency through status indicators.\\n- Examples include the author's seedling/budding/evergreen system and the epistemic statuses used by Gwern.net and Devon Zuegal.\\n\\n### Playful, Personal, and Experimental\\n- Encourages unique, non-homogenous sites built with web-native languages.\\n\\n### Intercropping & Content Diversity\\n- Includes various media types such as audio, video, and code.\\n\\n### Independent Ownership\\n- Focuses on controlling one's own space and data using open formats like HTML and markdown, outside of walled platforms like Medium or Facebook.\", 'brief_summary': \"Digital Gardening refers to a trend of creating free-form, evolving online knowledge spaces, akin to wikis, that prioritize contextual linking over reverse-chronological order. These 'gardens' are characterized by their less rigid, performative, and imperfect nature, encouraging continuous growth and public learning, contrasting with traditional blogs and ephemeral social media streams.\", 'detailed_summary': \"## Core Concept of Digital Gardening\\n- A departure from traditional blogs, emphasizing free-form, work-in-progress wikis.\\n- Ideas evolve and are linked by context, not reverse-chronological order.\\n- Characterized as less rigid, performative, and perfect, echoing the early web's ethos.\\n\\n## Evolution of the 'Digital Garden' Concept\\n- Mark Bernstein's 1998 essay 'Hypertext Gardens' first addressed user experience and content organization in the context of the '90s 'Navigation Problem'.\\n- A brief, unrelated usage appeared on Twitter in April 2007, where Rory Sutherland defined it as digital maintenance or 'faffing'.\\n- The modern concept is credited to Mike Caufield's 2015 keynote 'The Garden and the Stream', which positioned the garden as a long-term, explorable knowledge space in contrast to ephemeral social media 'streams'.\\n- Caufield's ideas gained traction in late 2018, amplified by Tom Critchlow's 'campfires' metaphor and Joel Hooks' 2019 writing on gardening as a process.\\n- Amy Hoy's argument that Moveable Type's 2001 launch standardized the reverse-chronological blog is cited as a contrast.\\n- By 2019-2020, the concept was expanded by Shaun Wang and Anne-Laure Le Cunff, discussed by the IndieWeb community, and covered by MIT Tech Review.\\n\\n## Community and Technological Support\\n- The trend's growth was supported by communities such as IndieWeb, Roam Research users, and followers of 'Building a Second Brain' and 'Learn in Public' philosophies.\\n- Early adopters were often developers utilizing tools like Netlify, Vercel, and static site generators (Jekyll, Gatsby).\\n- No-code tools like Obsidian, TiddlyWiki, and Notion now offer less customizable options for non-technical users.\\n\\n## Key Characteristics and Patterns\\n\\n### Topography over Timelines\\n- Prioritizes contextual, bi-directional links over chronological dates.\\n\\n### Continuous Growth\\n- Notes are never considered finished and are expected to evolve publicly.\\n\\n### Imperfection & Learning in Public\\n- Embraces a 'Domestic Cozy' approach, requiring transparency through status indicators.\\n- Examples include the author's seedling/budding/evergreen system and the epistemic statuses used by Gwern.net and Devon Zuegal.\\n\\n### Playful, Personal, and Experimental\\n- Encourages unique, non-homogenous sites built with web-native languages.\\n\\n### Intercropping & Content Diversity\\n- Includes various media types such as audio, video, and code.\\n\\n### Independent Ownership\\n- Focuses on controlling one's own space and data using open formats like HTML and markdown, outside of walled platforms like Medium or Facebook.\", 'tags': ['digital-gardening', 'knowledge-management', 